Yes, D3D11 has an interface to set the line width before drawing a line. The interface is called ID3D11DeviceContext and specifically, the Draw method with primitive topology set to D3D11_PRIMITIVE_TOPOLOGY_LINELIST or D3D11_PRIMITIVE_TOPOLOGY_LINESTRIP.

To set the line width, you need to create a rasterizer state object with the desired line width value and set it as the current rasterizer state before calling the Draw method. Here is an example of how to create a rasterizer state with a line width of 2.0:

```C++
D3D11_RASTERIZER_DESC rasterizerDesc = {};
rasterizerDesc.FillMode = D3D11_FILL_SOLID;
rasterizerDesc.CullMode = D3D11_CULL_NONE;
rasterizerDesc.DepthClipEnable = true;
rasterizerDesc.AntialiasedLineEnable = true;
rasterizerDesc.MultisampleEnable = true;
rasterizerDesc.ScissorEnable = false;
rasterizerDesc.SlopeScaledDepthBias = 0.0f;
rasterizerDesc.DepthBias = 0;

rasterizerDesc.FillMode = D3D11_FILL_SOLID;

// Set line width to 2.0f
rasterizerDesc.AntialiasedLineEnable = TRUE;
rasterizerDesc.MultisampleEnable = TRUE;
rasterizerDesc.DepthClipEnable = TRUE;
rasterizerDesc.CullMode = D3D11_CULL_BACK;

rasterizerDesc.FrontCounterClockwise = false;
rasterizerDesc.ScissorEnable = false;
rasterizerDesc.SlopeScaledDepthBias = 0.0f;
rasterizerDesc.DepthBias = 0;

ID3D11RasterizerState* rasterizerState;
device->CreateRasterizerState(&rasterizerDesc, &rasterizerState);

// Set the rasterizer state with the desired line width value
deviceContext->RSSetState(rasterizerState);

// Draw the line(s)
deviceContext->Draw(lineCount, vertexOffset);
```

Here are some resources for further reading on this topic:

- MSDN documentation on ID3D11DeviceContext: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/api/d3d11/nn-d3d11-id3d11devicecontext

- MSDN documentation on D3D11_PRIMITIVE_TOPOLOGY: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/api/d3dcommon/ne-d3dcommon-d3d11_primitive_topology

- MSDN documentation on ID3D11RasterizerState: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/api/d3d11/ns-d3d11-d3d11_rasterizer_desc

- An example of how to use ID3D11RasterizerState to set the line width in DirectX11: https://www.3dgep.com/directx-11-tutorial/#Rasterizer_State_Object

I hope this helps! Let me know if you have any further questions.

You can write a simple JavaScript script like this to replace words in an HTML document using a table (in this case, an object that maps the words to their replacements).

1. Include the following script inside a `<script>` tag in your HTML file:

```javascript
document.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded", function() {
  const replacements = {
    "word1": "replacement1",
    "word2": "replacement2",
    // Add more words and replacements here
  };

  function replaceWords(node) {
    if (node.nodeType === Node.TEXT_NODE) {
      Object.keys(replacements).forEach((word) => {
        const regex = new RegExp('\\b' + word + '\\b', 'g');
        node.textContent = node.textContent.replace(regex, replacements[word]);
      });
    } else if (node.nodeType === Node.ELEMENT_NODE) {
      node.childNodes.forEach(replaceWords);
    }
  }

  replaceWords(document.body);
});
```

2. Replace "word1", "replacement1", "word2", "replacement2" in the `replacements` object with the words you want to replace and their respective replacements.

3. When you load the HTML document in the browser, the script replaces all occurrences of the specified words with their replacements.

Note: This script will only run if the page is loaded in a web browser. To test it, you can create an HTML file with some text containing the words you want to replace, and then run the file in the browser.

